context: Pope Saint John XXIII (Latin: Ioannes XXIII; Italian: Giovanni XXIII) born <a0_0><b9_0>Angelo Giuseppe Roncalli<b9_0/><a0_0/>,[a] Italian pronunciation: [ˈandʒelo dʒuˈzɛppe roŋˈkalli]; <a1_0><b5_0>25 November 1881<b5_0/><a1_0/> – <a2_0><b6_0>3 June 1963<b6_0/><a2_0/>) reigned as Pope <b7_0>from <a3_0>28 October 1958 to his death in 1963<b7_0/><a3_0/> and was canonized on <b8_0>27 April 2014<b8_0/>. Angelo Giuseppe Roncalli was the fourth of fourteen children born to a family of sharecroppers who lived in a village in Lombardy. He was ordained to the priesthood on <a4_0>10 August 1904<a4_0/> and served in a number of posts, including papal nuncio in France and a delegate to Bulgaria, Greece and Turkey. In a consistory on 12 January 1953 Pope Pius XII made Roncalli a cardinal as the Cardinal-Priest of Santa Prisca in addition to naming him as the Patriarch of Venice.
